                        <h1><a name="57239"></a><a href="/blogs/readMore.html?id=57239">When Is Enough, Enough?</a></h1>
                        <div class="ItemInfo">[<a href="/blogs/selectBlog.html?id=2733&amp;articleId=57239" alt="Use this to refer to the specific blog entry">URL</a>] Posted on 4 August 2004 15:31,  <a href="/blogs/readMore.html?id=57239">0 comments in 0 threads.</a> Last comment on 4 August 2004 15:31.
                        </div>
                        <div>I've just posted a new update to the pre-playtest group. Things are getting so close to playtest for the Player's Compendium
                           now that I am getting kind of excited. Of course, I had high hopes that we would have been at this stage a few months ago.
                           Why hasn't this been the case? Well, it's not from working hard at this venture.
                           
                           <p>There is a lot of truth in the 80/20 rule. You know the one. "80 percent of the work goes into the last 20 percent of the
                              project." Unfortunately, this is the case with the revised books as well. If it had been simply a case of taking the original
                              content, shoving it around in a wordprocessor, slapping a coat of paint on it and pushing it out the door, then we would have
                              been there by now. Unfortunately, I have this little problem called "pride" that gets in the way of doing things this way.
                              Not the vain version of pride. Pride in having the opportunity to publish materials for my favorite fantasy game. And with
                              that pride comes "responsibility" -- and that means taking the time to produce the absolute best books that I possibly can.
                           </p>
                           
                           <p>How much effort does it take? Well, if we had the resources of a company like Hasbro, then we could afford to hire people
                              full-time to work on these projects. That doesn't mean we don't have resources, just that we don't have the luxury of eating
                              into them to produce books. So we throw time at this instead -- full-time commitment from me and the other RedBrick staff,
                              part-time commitment from our kind volunteers. I've had a couple of emails from people wondering how things are going, and
                              wondering about the state of the nation in the Earthdawn Classic world. Well, we're making steady progress toward the first
                              releases. And, they will be ready when they're ready. That hopefully still means 2004. But if it isn't, then please don't
                              be disappointed. It's not just one or two books we're talking about here...
                           </p>
                           
                           <p>When is enough, enough? At this stage, when we get to playtest and the playtesters come back with a resounding "cool" ...</p>
                           
                           <p>Take kaer, JAMES</p>
                        </div><br></td>
                  </tr>
